In article <Cwo4Bq.7Hx@cbnewsh.cb.att.com>, wcs@cbnewsh.cb.att.com (bill.stewart@pleasantonca.ncr.com) writes:
> ]2) Copyright (applicable everywhere the Berne convention applies), this
> ]   protects the actual representation of the algorithm (as either source
> ]   or executable code).
> ]3) Contractual (enhanced by some trade secret laws in the USA), this
> ]   protects the software through legal agreement.
> 
> Of course, you can't have something both protected by trade secret
> laws and also patented, since patents inherently require disclosure.

The same could also be said of copyright, although the deposit requirements
keep getting weakened.

Usually the lawyers seem to resort to a kitchen sink approach to intellectual
property protection.  Throw everything in, and hope something sticks.

